@Mean Old Lady --- Are you encouraging me to be anatomically technical? Which I'm happy to do every gnaw and then... if only to humerus.

I'll just say the ELBOW is articulation is  really only between the humerus and the olecranon process of the ulna. The radius, which is  'massive' at the wrist, tapers as it nears the ELBOW, and  doesn't form part of the actual  hinge joint; the radial head  lives inside a loop of connective tissue on the ulna, leaving the near end of the radius free to pivot on its long axis.  An odd arrangement, for sure, that makes the elbow a tricky joint in several ways, but invaluable in allowing the forearm to turn palm up/ palm down.

Without that, just imagine the contortions to operate your standard door-knob?

